  |          |          |       |      |
GUI      Database   Evidence  Alerts  Analytics/Audit
Dashboard Records   Storage   Mobile  Reporting

Core principle:

The camera pipeline must not directly control the entire application. It produces structured surveillance events. Other modules react to those events according to permissions, policies, rules, and configuration.

This keeps the UI responsive, reduces coupling, supports scaling, and allows future services or workers to be separated without redesigning the product.

Deployment principle:

Operational surveillance remains on the local edge. An edge synchronization gateway may send policy-approved records to the cloud through authenticated APIs. Cameras, local PostgreSQL, and local evidence storage are never exposed directly to the public internet, and the desktop client never embeds cloud database credentials.

Service strategy:

AISurv establishes three coarse deployment boundaries early: the JavaFX desktop client, the local edge backend, and the optional cloud control plane. The edge backend and cloud backend begin as separate modular monoliths with explicit module ownership and versioned APIs. They are not decomposed into many microservices by default. Capture, inference, notification, evidence, or analytics workers become independent services only when measured scaling, fault-isolation, hardware, deployment, or team-ownership requirements justify extraction.

