The desktop client and local edge backend become separate processes during M1, even when installed on the same workstation. The desktop calls a versioned local API and receives DTOs, view models, and live updates. It must not directly own database tables, Redis keys, AI inference, stream lifecycle, or evidence file management. The edge backend continues monitoring when the desktop closes or restarts. The current M0 prototype still contains direct desktop-process persistence and processing; this is implementation debt, not the target boundary.

4.1 Local Edge Responsibilities

- Discover and connect to cameras on the site network.
- Capture RTSP streams and run motion, object, behavior, and optional identity analysis locally.
- Persist camera configuration, events, incidents, audit records, settings, and evidence metadata in local PostgreSQL.
- Preserve snapshots and clips in local filesystem or MinIO storage according to retention policy.
- Authenticate local operators and enforce cached site permissions during cloud outages.
- Continue monitoring, local alerting, incident review, and evidence capture without cloud connectivity.
- Queue approved synchronization records in a durable transactional outbox.

4.2 Optional Cloud Control Plane Responsibilities

- Manage commercial tenants, sites, subscriptions, licensing, and device enrollment.
- Provide fleet health, remote administration, notification routing, and cross-site reporting.
- Store synchronized event summaries, health telemetry, audit summaries, and other policy-approved records.
- Distribute signed configuration and software-update metadata through controlled APIs.
- Enforce tenant isolation, cloud roles, data residency, retention, and regional deployment requirements.

The cloud control plane must not require direct access to camera networks, RTSP credentials, local PostgreSQL, or local object-storage credentials. Cloud PostgreSQL is reachable only by cloud backend services. Supabase may be selected as a managed PostgreSQL and platform provider, but edge and desktop clients still communicate through AISurv APIs rather than database or service-role credentials.

4.3 Connectivity and Synchronization Rules

- Edge-to-cloud connections are outbound only by default and use TLS with authenticated site identities.
- Local operation must tolerate an unavailable cloud control plane for an administrator-defined period.
- Synchronization is asynchronous, resumable, observable, and safe to retry.
- Every synchronized command or record has a stable identifier and idempotency behavior.
- A transactional outbox prevents committed local records from being lost between database commit and transmission.
- Cloud-issued commands are signed or authenticated, authorized for one tenant and site, audited, and acknowledged.
- Camera credentials, raw streams, biometric templates, and evidence remain local by default.
- Evidence or personal data is uploaded only when enabled by explicit policy, legal basis, role, and retention configuration.
- Conflict ownership is explicit: the edge owns live operational state; the cloud owns tenant, subscription, and fleet-level state; synchronized policy versions use versioned reconciliation.

4.4 Service Extraction Rules

- The JavaFX client, edge backend, and cloud control plane are independent deployment units with versioned contracts.
- The edge backend is a modular monolith first; camera, event, evidence, identity, notification, and synchronization modules have explicit internal boundaries.
- The cloud control plane is a separate modular monolith first and owns no site camera-processing responsibilities.
- A module is extracted only when it needs independent scaling, failure isolation, hardware placement, release cadence, or team ownership.
- RTSP capture and AI inference stay in the same edge process or local worker pool until measured GPU or camera-load requirements justify separation.
- Full video frames are not transported between network services by default; extraction requires a documented bandwidth, latency, ownership, and backpressure design.
- Extracted services own their persistence and contracts. Cross-service table access and a shared mutable database schema are prohibited.
- Distributed messaging is introduced for a demonstrated delivery need, not merely to label the architecture as microservices.

5. Separation of Concerns

5.1 Desktop UI Layer

Responsibilities:

- JavaFX application shell
- AtlantaFX theme and styling
- Dashboard page
- Live Monitor page
- Event Log page
- Incident Review page
- Camera and Zone Management pages
- AI Settings page
- Notification Settings page
- Face Registry page
- Reports and Analytics page
- Audit Log page
- Users and Roles page
- System Health page

Rules:

- UI updates happen on the JavaFX Application Thread.
- Database, stream, AI, network, and evidence work run in the separate edge backend or its workers.
- The UI should not directly access Hibernate repositories, Redis, RTSP connections, or raw evidence storage.
- The UI uses versioned command/query APIs and SSE subscriptions through generated or shared contract DTOs.

5.2 Application Service Layer

The application service layer runs inside the local edge backend as a modular monolith. It is the only desktop-facing boundary for local operational commands and queries.

Responsibilities:

- Coordinate business use cases.
- Validate commands.
- Check permissions.
- Call domain services and repositories.
- Return DTOs and view models to the UI.
- Hide persistence and infrastructure details from the desktop client.

Representative services:

- CameraApplicationService
- EventApplicationService
- IncidentReviewService
- DashboardService
- EvidenceApplicationService
- NotificationApplicationService
- UserRoleService
- SystemHealthService

5.3 Camera and Stream Layer

Responsibilities:

- ONVIF camera discovery
- Manual RTSP camera registration fallback
- Operator-approved camera registration
- Camera registration metadata
- RTSP connection lifecycle
- Stream health checks
- Reconnect policy
- Frozen-stream detection
- Frame capture
- Camera priority handling

CameraStreamWorker remains a stream ingestion worker. It captures frames and reports stream health. It must not own final AI decisions, event severity, database writes, or notification routing.

Commercial camera lifecycle:

Discover cameras
        |
Present discovered devices to authorised operator
        |
Operator enters or validates credentials
        |
Resolve or validate RTSP stream URI
        |
Operator assigns name, location, zone, priority, and enabled state
        |
Save registered camera to PostgreSQL
        |
StreamManager starts monitoring enabled cameras
        |
Health monitor updates live status and emits camera events

Discovery rules:

- ONVIF discovery is the preferred automatic discovery method.
- Discovered cameras are temporary candidates, not trusted production cameras.
- Operators must explicitly register discovered cameras before monitoring begins.
- Manual RTSP registration must remain supported because some cameras or NVRs have incomplete ONVIF support.
- Credentials must not be displayed casually or stored as plain text in the final commercial implementation.
- Camera registration, updates, disablement, and deletion must be audited.

Camera registration data should include:

- Display name
- RTSP URL
- ONVIF service URL where available
- Manufacturer and model where available
- Host/IP address
- Location, building, floor, and zone
- Priority
- Enabled state
- Credential reference
- Health status
- Created and updated timestamps

5.4 Frame Processing Layer

Responsibilities:

- Frame packaging and timestamping
- Frame queueing
- Resizing and preprocessing
- Frame skipping and controlled inference intervals
- Priority scheduling
- Snapshot candidate extraction

This layer protects CPU/GPU resources and ensures high-priority cameras are processed first under load.

5.5 AI Detection Layer

Responsibilities:

- Motion/activity gating
- Person detection
- Object detection
- Vehicle, animal, and other-object classification
- Confidence scoring
- Zone-aware filtering

MotionDetector remains strategically important as the inexpensive first activity gate. Expensive inference should only run when activity, zone policy, camera priority, and resources justify it.

5.6 Tracking Layer

Responsibilities:

- Assign temporary human track IDs.
- Track people across frames.
- Detect movement state.
- Reduce duplicate alerts.
- Mark zone entry and exit.
- Optionally support cross-camera correlation in enterprise deployments.

Movement states include stationary, walking, running, group movement, and unknown.

5.7 Behavior Analysis Layer

Responsibilities:

- Loitering detection
- Restricted-zone entry detection
- After-hours movement detection
- Multiple-people-running detection
- Fight or commotion detection
- Fall or accident detection
- Crowd activity analysis

Behavior decisions should use multi-frame confirmation, zone rules, confidence thresholds, and context to reduce false positives.

5.8 Optional Face Intelligence Layer

Face detection and recognition are optional and tightly governed.

Rules:

- Disabled unless explicitly enabled by authorised administrators.
- Limited to approved zones and approved institutional use cases.
- Controlled by roles and permissions.
- Audited for all sensitive administrative and access actions.
- Results must be cautious: known match, unknown, watchlist candidate, insufficient confidence, not visible, not required, or not authorised.

Face recognition must not be treated as an unquestionable identity decision.

5.9 Event Engine

The Event Engine converts observations into structured surveillance events.

It decides:

- Event type
- Severity
- Evidence requirements
- Notification requirements
- Cooldown and duplicate suppression
- Escalation rules
- Operator acknowledgement requirements

Severity levels:

- Low: ordinary informational events or normal movement
- Medium: loitering warnings or impaired camera state
- High: restricted-zone entry, after-hours human movement, unexpected group running
- Critical: fight, major commotion, suspected fall, accident, or emergency condition

5.10 Persistence Layer

Local PostgreSQL is the source of truth for site operational records. Cloud PostgreSQL is a separate source of truth for tenant, subscription, fleet, and synchronized cloud records. Neither database is accessed directly across the edge-cloud boundary. Hibernate/JPA is used through repositories, Flyway manages schema migrations, and HikariCP manages connection pooling.

Stored data includes:

- Users, roles, and permissions
- Cameras, groups, zones, and priorities
- Events and incident records
- Evidence metadata
- Notification records and device endpoints
- System settings
- AI model settings and thresholds
- Audit logs
- Retention policies

Large media files should not be stored directly in relational tables. PostgreSQL stores metadata and references. Evidence storage stores actual snapshots and clips.

5.11 Redis and Local Caching

Redis is used for shared fast-changing state and short-lived data.

Good Redis uses:

- Dashboard summary cache
- Recent events cache
- Camera online/offline state
- Active incident state
- Notification cooldowns
- Duplicate event suppression
- Temporary QR pairing tokens
- SSE fan-out support
- Future lightweight event streaming through Redis Streams if needed

Redis is not the source of truth. Critical records still persist to PostgreSQL.

Caffeine is used as a local in-process cache for frequently read data such as camera metadata, zone policies, user permissions, system settings, and AI thresholds.

5.12 Evidence Management Layer

Responsibilities:

- Capture snapshots for high-value events.
- Preserve short incident clips where configured.
- Link evidence to event records.
- Enforce retention policies.
- Protect evidence integrity.
- Control access and export permissions.
- Audit sensitive evidence access.

Storage strategy:

- Local filesystem for prototype and small deployments.
- Local MinIO or another S3-compatible store for durable commercial edge deployments.
- Optional cloud object storage for explicitly approved replication, remote incident workflows, or archival.
- Evidence stays local by default and is never copied to the cloud merely because cloud connectivity is enabled.

5.13 Notification Layer

Responsibilities:

- Mobile alert routing
- Secure QR device pairing
- Device enrollment and revocation
- Notification rules and subscriptions
- Escalation for unacknowledged critical events
- Notification history and delivery status

Rules:

- QR pairing codes must expire.
- Scanning a QR code alone must not grant permanent access.
- Devices must be linked to authenticated users or approved roles.
- Notification payloads must respect role permissions and avoid unnecessary sensitive data.

5.14 Dashboard Analytics Layer

Responsibilities:

- Live event counts
- Camera status summaries
- Active incident counts
- Severity distribution
- Recent event feed
- Processing load
- Notification status
- System health summary

SSE is used for server-to-client live updates such as metrics, counts, status changes, and event notifications.

SSE must not be used for RTSP video, high-frequency frame transport, or bidirectional operator commands. Operator actions should use command APIs or application services.

5.15 Security, Privacy, and Governance Layer

Responsibilities:

- Authentication
- Roles and permissions
- Session control
- Access restrictions for live feeds, events, evidence, settings, and face data
- Privacy and retention governance
- Administrative control of notification endpoints
- Sensitive action auditing

Security-sensitive actions must be audited, including evidence access, evidence export, biometric profile changes, camera configuration changes, AI threshold changes, device enrollment, device revocation, role updates, and incident acknowledgement or escalation.

5.16 Observability Layer

Responsibilities:

- Application logs
- Metrics
- Traces
- Health checks
- System performance dashboards

Important metrics:

- Camera uptime
- Frame processing rate
- AI inference latency
- Queue depth
- Dropped frames
- Database latency
- Redis latency
- SSE client count
- Notification failures
- Evidence storage usage
- CPU, GPU, and memory load

