12. Design Philosophy

AISurv is governed by these principles:

- Capture only what is needed.
- Process only what matters.
- Alert only when it is important.
- Store only useful and policy-approved evidence.
- Display only actionable operational information.
- Protect sensitive capabilities through permissions, auditing, and privacy controls.
- Scale without changing the product purpose.

Conclusion

AISurv is designed as a professional JavaFX desktop-operated intelligent surveillance platform. The revised architecture preserves the existing RTSP capture, motion detection, person detection, live monitoring, and event logging baseline while moving the system toward a scalable commercial design.

The target deployment is local-first and cloud-enabled. Camera ingestion, AI inference, operational PostgreSQL, and evidence remain at each site, while an optional cloud control plane provides tenant management, licensing, fleet health, remote summaries, notifications, and approved analytics through secure APIs. Supabase or another managed PostgreSQL platform may host cloud data, but it is never accessed directly by the desktop or edge runtime.

The system should first focus on strong core architecture, clean separation of concerns, reliable offline operation, and a reliable event-driven pipeline. Cloud synchronization follows explicit data-ownership and privacy rules. Kubernetes should remain a planned cloud and enterprise deployment target, not a first-phase implementation burden.
